European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, Nazi occupation.
Possibly it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have convinced me that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever — one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated — is a mistake.
That's like if one part of a room could be heated while the other part remained cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event elicits an echo throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies—what is in Europe's interest—then a number of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from the top down.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more interconnected they are, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it becomes; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that the central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy, which abandoned European solidarity and led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call to vigilance.
One must confront the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough for only governments to act.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for safety is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept for its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make quick decisions and to swiftly implement collective decisions—reforms that were deemed necessary by recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of overall European security, require interventions outside the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate may not come, even though intervention is in the interest of many people, of all of Europe, indeed of human civilization itself.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, there are still further matters to address in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of the enlarged civil society in Europe.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, people acted only timidly.
These shortcomings were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot remain forever dependent on the United States, especially regarding European issues.
It must be able to reach its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can continue to exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves itself incapable of agreeing on means and methods to protect human rights, not only on its own territory but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such an EU enlargement is only feasible if it proceeds hand in hand with a determined reform of the EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting commitment to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
A related point of institutional reform is the question of how to assure smaller states that they will not simply be outvoted by larger ones, while at the same time adequately taking into account the size of each individual state.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber will not be elected directly, but will be chosen by the parliaments of the member states from among their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU — that is, the current Parliament — would therefore reflect the size of individual member states, while the second chamber would increase equality, with the same number of representatives for each country.
Eventually, these changes will require the EU to have a clear and understandable constitution—a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and objectives of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a constitutional framework would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Eurosceptics.
However, it would help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, to better understand it, to see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
